hydra-llm (0.1.9-1) unstable; urgency=low

  * New `hydra-llm reasoning` subcommand controlling how a model's
    "thinking" / chain-of-thought is exposed. Accepted values:
      none      thinking stays inline in `content` (default, most
                plug-and-play; e.g. `<think>...</think>` blocks).
      deepseek  thinking is split out into a separate
                `reasoning_content` field on each streamed delta and on
                the final message. Clients can render it as a fold-out.
      hide      strip thinking before returning to the client
                (--reasoning-format auto on llama-server).
      off       don't pass the flag; use llama-server's compiled-in
                default (varies by build).
    Bare `reasoning` shows the current value and the accepted set.
    Persists to ~/.config/hydra-llm/config.yaml. Takes effect on
    newly started containers; restart running ones to apply.
  * Default for new installs is `none`, so Gemma's thinking blocks
    are visible in the response by default rather than silently
    stripped.

 -- Ramazan Yavuz <yavuzramazan1994@gmail.com>  Wed, 06 May 2026 00:00:00 +0000

hydra-llm (0.1.8-1) unstable; urgency=low

  * New: model containers now launch with `--predict -1` by default,
    so responses to clients that don't send `max_tokens` are no longer
    silently truncated at llama-server's built-in 128 tokens. The
    model now stops on EOS or when context fills up, which is what
    most users expect. Clients that do send `max_tokens` are
    unaffected; they still win.
  * New `hydra-llm predict` subcommand to change this default.
    Accepted values:
      uncapped    no cap (default)
      off         don't pass --predict; revert to llama-server's 128
      <integer>   positive integer, e.g. 2048
    Run with no args to show the current value and the accepted set.
    Takes effect on newly started containers; restart running ones
    to apply.

 -- Ramazan Yavuz <yavuzramazan1994@gmail.com>  Wed, 06 May 2026 00:00:00 +0000

hydra-llm (0.1.7-1) unstable; urgency=low

  * Fix: the `hydrallm` short alias was missing from the actual .deb in
    0.1.5 / 0.1.6. CI builds via `scripts/build-deb.sh` (not via the
    Makefile or `dh_install`), and that script wasn't creating the
    symlink. Added there too. After upgrading, `which hydrallm`
    resolves to /usr/bin/hydrallm and runs the same CLI.

 -- Ramazan Yavuz <yavuzramazan1994@gmail.com>  Wed, 06 May 2026 00:00:00 +0000

hydra-llm (0.1.6-1) unstable; urgency=low

  * Catalog resolver now accepts a GGUF filename (with or without the
    `.gguf` extension) anywhere a catalog id is taken: `start`, `stop`,
    `download`, `chat`, `api`, etc. Exact match; id wins on collisions.
  * New `hydra-llm autostart [id]` subcommand. Writes a user-level
    systemd unit (`~/.config/systemd/user/hydra-llm-autostart.service`)
    that runs `hydra-llm start <id>` when you log in. Run with no
    args to see current state. `hydra-llm autostart --off` removes
    the unit. No root needed; the model id stays in user config.

 -- Ramazan Yavuz <yavuzramazan1994@gmail.com>  Wed, 06 May 2026 00:00:00 +0000

hydra-llm (0.1.5-1) unstable; urgency=low

  * `hydra-llm start` no longer requires a model id when exactly one
    model is downloaded; it auto-picks that one. With zero downloaded
    it points to `hydra-llm list-online`/`download`; with more than
    one it lists the candidate ids. Explicit `start <id>` is unchanged.
  * New `hydrallm` command, a symlink to `hydra-llm`, for less typing.
    Both names work everywhere; the .deb, user-install, and dev-install
    paths all ship it.
  * Fix: `hydra-llm start` no longer falsely reports "already running"
    when a same-named container is sitting in `Exited` state. The check
    now requires `State == running`; stale exited containers are
    removed and recreated cleanly so the model actually comes back up.

 -- Ramazan Yavuz <yavuzramazan1994@gmail.com>  Wed, 06 May 2026 00:00:00 +0000

hydra-llm (0.1.4-1) unstable; urgency=low

  * New `hydra-llm help [subcommand]` subcommand. Previously only
    `-h`/`--help` worked; typing `hydra-llm help` errored with "invalid
    choice". Now `hydra-llm help` prints top-level help and
    `hydra-llm help <subcommand>` prints help for that subcommand.

